here\">\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f51\u0fb2\u0f42\u0f0b<\/span>, and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f0b<\/span> is used after vowels and the consonants <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f0b<\/span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f62\u0f0b<\/span>, and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">In the spoken language, this rule is usually not followed, and the form <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span> is used in all contexts. Some speakers do, however, follow the rule. In this case, the \/w\/ of the suffix \/wa\/ disappears, and the consonant is then doubled:<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f0b<\/span> becomes pronounced <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f55\u0f74\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f0b<\/span> becomes pronounced <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f55\u0f74\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5a\u0f62\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f0b<\/span> becomes pronounced <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5a\u0f62\u0f0b\u0f62\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">The suffix <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span> is associated only with the past tense form of the verb, and refers to a past perfective action.<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5e\u0f74\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span> but not *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5e\u0f74\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f5f\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span> but not *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f5f\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b<\/span><\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">A nominalized verb may be followed by a demonstrative, an indefinite article, or other determinants such as any substantive.<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f42\u0f66\u0f74\u0f44\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f7a\u0f0b\u0f5a\u0f7c\u0f0d<\/span> \u201cThose that [you] mentioned....\u201d<\/li> <\/ul>","title":""}]}
