{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"5150","authors":[{"fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre","id":"6"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:28 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:28 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">Historically speaking, of the nominalizing suffixes, the suffix <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">པ་</span> occupies an essential place to the extent that it is the basic marker of nominalization in Literary Tibetan. In Standard Spoken Tibetan, however, it has far fewer functions.</p> <p class=\"Paragraph\">In Literary Tibetan, the suffix པ་ sometimes appears in the variant form བ་. But be careful: this modification applies only to verb suffixes, and not to suffixes with other functions such as noun or adjective suffixes. Thus Standard Tibetan says <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁང་པ་</span> “house” and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྟོང་པ་</span> “empty,” not *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁང་བ་</span> and *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྟོང་བ་</span>.</p> <p class=\"Paragraph\">In Literary Tibetan the variants <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">པ་</span> and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བ་</span> are used as follows:</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">པ་</span> is used after the consonants <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ག་</span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ད་</span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ན་</span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བ་</span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མ་</span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ས་</span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ད་དྲག་</span>, and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">པ་</span></li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བ་</span> is used after vowels and the consonants <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ང་</span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འ་</span>, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ར་</span>, and <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལ་</span></li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">In the spoken language, this rule is usually not followed, and the form <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">པ་</span> is used in all contexts. Some speakers do, however, follow the rule. In this case, the /w/ of the suffix /wa/ disappears, and the consonant is then doubled:</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ནང་བ་</span> becomes pronounced <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ནང་ང་</span></li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཕུལ་བ་</span> becomes pronounced <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཕུལ་ལ་</span></li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཚར་བ་</span> becomes pronounced <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཚར་ར་</span></li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The suffix <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">པ་</span> is associated only with the past tense form of the verb, and refers to a past perfective action.</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཞུས་པ་</span> but not *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཞུ་པ་</span></li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བཟས་པ་</span> but not *<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཟ་པ་</span></li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">A nominalized verb may be followed by a demonstrative, an indefinite article, or other determinants such as any substantive.</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">གསུངས་པ་དེ་ཚོ།</span> “Those that [you] mentioned....”</li> </ul>","title":""}]}
